{"id": "229bda2a360a0c956e9b7c3134ab94b4bad7975b5d1ea2ee285afd5e15d3bb2f", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:0", "text": "Like all texture style nodes, this node takes a manifold that describes either a 2D or 3D domain to apply a Worley noise texture to. The default behavior, if no manifold is attached, is to apply over P in 3D. This node computes"}
{"id": "4e57c342045c309a69e3ad9c5bf5d9876cacf5e68b56993c2decc5c7d80a2c3b", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:1", "text": "Worley noise"}
{"id": "2a848a0b55e7ac1523772013940427aed0032f442641d6d279a32d68c18694e3", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:2", "text": ", as described by Steven Worley."}
{"id": "d1e3d635bf4084423df941ecf74cd1709a4efa9811a050cc191885400fe4a027", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:4", "text": "Surface Position"}
{"id": "0cd4048b786093a9ee031641b4e38b38fdf142d5b04de850bf325ba993abab30", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:5", "text": "The noise can be computed based on the"}
{"id": "709fe7f143bc3c1afe3c9f14565b798314f47dd342a7730df546f478ceb3e5f3", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:6", "text": "Current Position"}
{"id": "ba4b7cfc09d78634ff53cd009a1e4c2507b4743429b2e538e2e01c8acee00138", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:7", "text": "or the"}
{"id": "579996376b0f5f3926642832076464a78dafd8c8328e5625ecc07a19e114e8b8", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:11", "text": "Undisplaced Position"}
{"id": "4ff23c279f8ca82275babe7ce7963f83c4d33ee35bde9dacb74fd6b7097a8e47", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:9", "text": "(the position of the surface prior to displacement)."}
{"id": "c848ab50f5f05803ec189c1929892f987d0768d454c500b94447949883cf3983", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:10", "text": "If you want your displacement and shading patterns to match, use the"}
{"id": "16b6668d9831a1b8d2d003496db6a62b7f525df6c556d7c04681fbed2251c845", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:13", "text": "Frequency"}
{"id": "6bf4925860e16cfb0e707cd9a6654cf85847bd375c6bcc516cd29f6f2335233a", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:14", "text": "Controls the size of the cells. Higher frequencies make smaller cells."}
{"id": "eab00280e12121205e8302a3d40c4805ea1fe52b75e832c29676868082f0afa7", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:15", "text": "Distance Metric"}
{"id": "1976d96e1dd2d1eb4d9397fc129de0435b66c9eba218bdb16cb6bfe1f7f2bc53", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:16", "text": "The means to measure distances to neighboring cells. Manhattan distance gives more rectangular shapes and Euclidian distance gives more spherical shapes."}
{"id": "0e53881e722c8631d723a211a5fb52d5b1a3fa6218921f8563b05ed76b3d6bed", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:17", "text": "Euclidean"}
{"id": "451b82cb55639f55d8cfaac5910cb3cf42e5edd0022b783756a8ac6f7dd58025", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:18", "text": "Computes the euclidean distance to the nearest points. It looks a bit more pointy than Squared Euclidean distance."}
{"id": "eb2c302deddc499f56349448a83b5233bed3cf7108ac851aa8d0847bcf27ade0", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:19", "text": "Euclidean Squared"}
{"id": "295806c98f480a6ab7989d9f1172553f801380730ad10d8419aa9e7557b4c13e", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:20", "text": "Computes the squared euclidean distance to the nearest points. It looks rounder than pure Euclidean distance and more organic."}
{"id": "b519d05a7c6caa5dc247154a14e4f247652bb6c000e0f4c203a2efd4984c2696", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:21", "text": "Manhattan"}
{"id": "201836683b6d5e4085e26d86764b29f1880d413fca8a6b768f94395a107e7e64", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:22", "text": "Inspired by the grid-like organization of Manhattan, this is the distance to the nearest points when you can only travel around the cell's boundaries."}
{"id": "793d649ab4bab9d0fccf94f26b729cfb1b3934d633ca67b047d841a4dde3b04d", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:23", "text": "Chebyshev"}
{"id": "0e0a53726bd0a6c74e0ba25de27c245c08b7506a356ed231f600af51148f56fd", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:24", "text": "Named after"}
{"id": "198a28f54dae2fe230f511786d1c78ab61d67ab218b503da0ee049e7b635a50c", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:25", "text": "Pafnutty Chebyshev"}
{"id": "c61568c23ec44ce5c539b1a315704f3945b8ebec0883b99a640146ee035f5f7d", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:26", "text": ", it is also known as the Chessboard Distance. It is somewhat similar to the Manhattan distance, but with 45 degrees rotation."}
{"id": "60ec6e166bcaca52355919230cdc23fff33aa3b02825c75e8ae56cece24c106c", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:28", "text": "Minkowski"}
{"id": "475721808b7bfb63fe36c84011607e53534af95d4dbdaf18ddf6043157568022", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:29", "text": "is a generalization of both euclidean and Manhattan distance. The exponent will make the pattern transition from Euclidian to Manhattan."}
{"id": "7fd8c936e61e38cfd94f40a03b9c9850aac47cd0cb7e96f9c315c4547d330816", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:30", "text": "Minkowski is more expensive than the other distance metrics, but it is fine for displacement as you will pay the cost only once when the geometry is displaced."}
{"id": "91fbe4c855fbe0759f01c98185f0e5b1317146f3371bb32e0470f226ac26f42b", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:31", "text": "Jitter"}
{"id": "7a5f0b6ef04cd3221e9ca40d9dcbd9215c89cb1d09e8d55cb080f510eb1bcb04", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:32", "text": "Controls the distortion of the cells."}
{"id": "ab861dc170dc2e43224e45278d3d31a675b9ebc34c9b0f48c066ca1eeaed8ee6", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:33", "text": "C1"}
{"id": "24732eb226b66a4cf019eef447a0833e4a68c6890a020b3dbfe2bf2a3898bbc4", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:34", "text": "Multiplier for the distances to the first feature."}
{"id": "9685eb765661ea3b95f31e1bb3c3b5501d0c2acdf353feeaa4d8fe32f95f77fb", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:35", "text": "C2"}
{"id": "192112034d1d3993e580b0ce47d08439f421fef79e9392eeb873878fb23907da", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:36", "text": "Multiplier for the distance to the second feature."}
{"id": "08f580ae1c24ec0f03952226f57f29a2f2edccd68cf7f44545bab3d16996268b", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:37", "text": "Minkowski Exponent"}
{"id": "ba0954f479f3db25b528e96901378fba77039f297b38a38205d100231b221385", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:38", "text": "Makes the distance transition smoothly from Manhattan (1.0) to Euclidean (2.0) to weird un-explored territories."}
{"id": "e0e492707f85ff1f9c23155494a54382b52bf34888091adc7a6bb338ef78f88d", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:39", "text": "Shape"}
{"id": "450fd14822aec0b2adb86d1b69a9b37572b436e8b705248d932628d3377575f3", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:40", "text": "Modifies the computed distances to create different shapes. The example below uses c1 = 1.0 and c2 = 0.0."}
{"id": "ea78eab70ff235505d98a49b89ffcf3d6525cea843bbd8057e8c85d08c385853", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:42", "text": "Causes resulting distances to be clamped to the range 0.0 to 1.0."}
{"id": "d0f631ca1ddba8db3bcfcb9e057cdc98d0379f1bee00e75a545147a27dadd982", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:43", "text": "c1"}
{"id": "9c0abe51c6e6655d81de2d044d4fb194931f058c0426c67c7285d8f5657ed64a", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:44", "text": "c2"}
{"id": "fc95537d4dc1c2cd3e9240d069d0744f4d0cae5182aa3710205cc42a7461e375", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:45", "text": "distancemetric"}
{"id": "c9d11b6fa5813be2d2359341561b903d360a422e44005210c40eb0e0ed982bdf", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:46", "text": ": Euclidean"}
{"id": "7e04f2ffb9334e3d19a15c949a73818d4b271b0e713dbfad612b29491b46bc1b", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:47", "text": "Invert"}
{"id": "95dd0e5f0e9ca3206a8afb36840163699a97eddd02427743720145d5cc61f1c0", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:48", "text": "Inverts the final pattern."}
{"id": "fe1d3cda4f2dfad4337360560d9435373e07a03af63fcd7ce88c0982e5bc19cf", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:49", "text": "Random Scale"}
{"id": "72e35c5c946d5ccd134d5c14d0881d139d4d6081c472a1a5430060fab334d439", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:50", "text": "This will randomly scale the features' amplitude and give a slightly more regular appearance."}
{"id": "896c8d988deee74102c4c55354a35dcbf874c6d03213362b8d863cf2f79a50e3", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:51", "text": "Random Scale Center"}
{"id": "eea40e6d4644761ddea708461ebfed275427bf772b666dd66e6f6795f442075d", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:52", "text": "This is applying a an offset to the signal before applying the random scale. Use this to create more variations."}
{"id": "c0ef6aca74f4483d5d101dae527dbf5167c8e452937ba6fbf7ea41366fb12d37", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:54", "text": "The manifold over which to apply the noise. (The default is P)."}
{"id": "ba71a7c085ac16c7de307e2e5aa8c79dbf1bdf5a8f5c762508150f6f2ca94568", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:56", "text": "Adjust Output"}
{"id": "1aa6cfeeea19be4fbc48af4632be06cabff3dbbdf85d83a7b4d87a7cbff4130f", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:57", "text": "Color Scale"}
{"id": "357de7170a2a222705b18022e71d03f3ccfaa3e29f07d77afef37049ca7c6318", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:58", "text": "A multiplier for the color values in a texture can be used to adjust brightness or manipulate individual color channels"}
{"id": "c54f3e0aa08775c55e47d2cf166b9abf18efa1edd69d16a07effb5ef590201d4", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:59", "text": "Color Offset"}
{"id": "53974a1945e8609215f7432f457ea84d46c68c98bfe25df5e3a212b92cef82f0", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:60", "text": "Apply an offset to the result, shifting the colors of the result"}
{"id": "46cf5c71d429968d1d70ed3bdf7df7658dde598a7f93d698f3fe8fb55890ec46", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:61", "text": "Float Scale"}
{"id": "fd1e60522b7fb288b5deb2c038d190e183ef97c591351d9a15b78772570ca8b6", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:62", "text": "Scalar Float value"}
{"id": "3c4a9da2ced3ea1f9286121722248c6a3d226a131039d9d546f0468a55acc769", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:63", "text": "Float Offset"}
{"id": "bf954cffaafd46c55175edd028e3698f819a16fd997536fec0df2e0c9cfa72d5", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:64", "text": "Float Offset value"}
{"id": "20cee54d3870761a41a354946a213694c0612e819dc7d1e21f529a8e727fb539", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:66", "text": "resultF"}
{"id": "34dba36dffead6227925a55623971696467c970c4fac3295d94fe336fc807fa0", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:67", "text": "The result of Worley noise texture."}
{"id": "cd1076e32fc7c3560ab2775e84b2ee954de8f0931851f76b7135ff374e3390e2", "item_id": "17c9c3ef8f:69", "text": "The texture as a monochrome color."}
